    "data": {
      "title": "Leap of sheep",
      "topics": [],
      "solution": "N = int(input())\nheights = list(map(int, input().split()))\n\nmini_of_next = [0] * N # mini_of_next[i] = min(heights[i:N]) \nmini_of_next[N-1] = heights[N-1]\n\nmini_of_prev = [0] * N # mini_of_prev[i] = min(heights[0:i+1])\nmini_of_prev[0] = heights[0]\n\nfor i in range(1, N):\n    mini_of_prev[i] = min(heights[i], mini_of_prev[i-1])\n    mini_of_next[N-1-i] = min(heights[N-1-i], mini_of_next[N-i])\n \nmaxi_difficulty = 0\nfor mid in range(1, N-1):\n    if heights[mid] > mini_of_prev[mid] and heights[mid] > mini_of_next[mid]:\n        difficulty = 2 * heights[mid] - mini_of_next[mid] - mini_of_prev[mid]\n        maxi_difficulty = max(maxi_difficulty, difficulty)\n\nprint(maxi_difficulty)",
      "statement": "Bob is training his sheep for the annual competition <<Leap of Sheep>>.\n\nHis training ground is composed of [[N]] piles of dirt of varying heights, evenly spaced.\n\nA <<leap>> is a jump between 3 piles of dirt in increasing index order (of heights [[h1]], [[h2]], [[h3]]), where the middle pile is <<strictly higher>> than the other two. The piles do not have to be next to each other: the sheep can jump over any number of piles, regardless of their height.\nThe <<difficulty>> of a leap is the difference between [[h2]] and [[h1]] plus the difference between [[h2]] and [[h3]].\n\nBob asks you to find the <<most difficult leap>> in his training ground, in order to perform well on the competition.",
